    <node id="1. The sighting of the mysterious space hulk was made through a telescope from a distance of ten thousand miles. It appeared different from any ship they had seen before, with a much larger size than any Foundation Yards ship. Its appearance was alien and it had an unusual hull material with tiny whorls that seemed unstable or possibly alive.&#10;2. The initial reactions of those who observed the space hulk through the telescope were shock and excitement. They immediately started counting their share of the salvage money, indicating their assumption that the ship was abandoned or in distress and could be claimed as salvage. The ship's large size and unusual appearance added to the sense of intrigue and potential value.&#10;3. The ship's origin is unknown, but its trajectory from Coma Berenices and alien appearance suggest that it came from distant stars or even beyond. Its hyperbolic orbit around the Sun will take it out into interstellar space again, indicating its inability to sustain itself in a planetary system.&#10;4. Given the potential value of the materials and technology aboard the ship, it would be wise to proceed with examining it cautiously while also acknowledging the risks and uncertainties surrounding its origin and purpose. There may be ethical considerations to take into account when claiming salvage rights, especially if the origins of the ship are unknown and it may belong to another civilization. It would be important to approach the situation with care and respect for possible cultural or legal implications." />
    <node id=" reported it from the forward scope position. I assumed it was a Foundation ship. The Holcomb Foundation was founded for the purpose of developing spaceflight, and as the years went by it took on the whole responsibility for the building and dispatching of space ships. Never in history had there been any real evidence of extra-terrestrial intelligent life, and when the EMV Triangle proved barren, we all just assumed that the Universe was man's own particular oyster. That kind of unreasoning arrogance is as hard to explain as it is to correct.&#10; &#10; There were plenty of ships being lost in space, and immediately that Spinelli's report from up forward got noised about the Maid every one of us started mentally counting up his share of the salvage money. All this before we were within ten thousand miles of the hulk!&#10; &#10; All spaceships look pretty much alike, but as I sat at the telescope I saw that there was something different about this one. At such a distance I couldn't get too much detail in our small three inch glass, but I could see that the hulk was big—bigger than any ship I'd ever seen before. I had the radar fixed on her and then I retired with my slide rule to Control." />
    <node id="1. The signal from the starship is winking out feebly, suggesting that the hand holding the lamp that is blinking out the message is shaking and the mind conceiving the words is failing. This makes it difficult for the narrator and Spinelli to read the signal.&#10;2. Spinelli believes that Zaleski has disobeyed orders regarding the gold because he saw Spinelli murmuring something to Zaleski, which created tension and distrust in the air. Spinelli may have been trying to form an alliance with Zaleski or inform him of the Captain's plan to claim the treasure for himself, leading Spinelli to suspect that Zaleski has disobeyed orders regarding the gold." />
    <node id="The greedy and hasty crew members of the Maid ship were Spinelli, Shelley, Cohn, Marvin, and Zaleski. They were a rough bunch of men who were more interested in high pay and hard living than in advancing civilization. Their unreasoning and unthinking love for gold led them to take over a derelict ship, which turned out to be a trap, resulting in their deaths. They missed the advancements made in space travel after the Maid's class became outdated, as they paid for their greed with all the years of their lives, leaving the speaker, their skipper, alone on a golden ship." />
