    <node id="The plan for repairing the damaged spaceship involves jury-rigging a spare pulse-jet and bringing the ship down under its own power. Mister Marvin and Zaleski are tasked with assembling the spare pulse-jet, while the protagonist, who is apparently the Commander, will take charge of provisioning the ship. This includes checking the compartments they found and installing oxy-generators aboard. Once these tasks are completed, they are to report to the protagonist in his quarters.&#10;&#10;The properties of the ship's metal hull do not directly impact the plan for repairing the ship. However, the fact that the metal is a form of gold may have implications for the financial aspect of the salvage operation. The protagonist initially expresses excitement about the potential value of the materials and technology aboard the ship, so it is possible that they plan to sell the gold hull for a profit once repairs are complete. This would provide additional motivation for the crew to successfully repair and salvage the spaceship." />
    <node id="1. The narrator's fear and physical exhaustion were caused by their exposure to a mysterious devil-metal from beyond the stars. This metal had drawn energy from the narrator and their crew, causing them to age rapidly and become weak.&#10;2. When referring to the &quot;devil's metal,&quot; the narrator is talking about the same unidentified metal that was transformed into gold. This metal is of unknown origin and has the ability to draw energy from its environment to find stability as a terrestrial element, in this case, transforming into gold. The narrator pursues the ship carrying this devil-metal with increasing acceleration, ultimately leading to their discovery and subsequent illness caused by the metal's energy-draining properties." />
    <node id="1. The &quot;poor, old&quot; former spaceman, who is known as Captain Midas in the story, holds the secret of a cursed treasure that he and his crew discovered in a derelict spaceship. The treasure was composed of a mysterious devil-metal from beyond the stars, which brought wealth but also rapid aging and illness to those who came into contact with it. Despite being part of a generation known for not laying hands on valuable things, Captain Midas and his greedy crew took over the derelict ship, leading to their deaths and leaving Captain Midas as the only survivor. The experience left him looking eighty at the age of thirty-two, impoverished, and isolated in a hospital cot, waiting for the weight of years he never lived to drag him under." />
    <edge source="The story suggests that the narrator, referred to as &quot;Captain&quot; or &quot;sir,&quot; refused Spinelli's request to be part of the prize crew for the derelict ship because he suspected that Spinelli was motivated by greed after seeing the gold-hunger in his eyes. The Captain wanted to keep a close hand on Spinelli, so he assigned him to stay on board the Maid with him instead. Additionally, when the Captain refused to let Spinelli go, Spinelli became angry and accused the Captain of planning to cheat him of his rightful share of the derelict treasure ship. Therefore, the Captain's decision to refuse Spinelli's request was likely motivated by a desire to maintain control of the situation and prevent any conflicts or mutinies arising from greed over the gold." target=" him what it was, and it seemed to me that his very soul reached out for the stuff, so sharp and clear was the meaning of the expression on his heavy face.&#10; &#10; &quot;Mister Spinelli!&quot; I snapped, &quot;In the future knock before entering my quarters!&quot;&#10; &#10; Reluctantly his eyes left the lump of gold and met mine. &quot;From the derelict, Captain?&quot; There was an imperceptible pause between the last two words.&#10; &#10; I ignored his question and made a mental note to keep a close hand on the rein with him. Spinelli was big and dangerous.&#10; &#10; &quot;Speak your piece, Mister,&quot; I ordered sharply.&#10; &#10; &quot;Mister Cohn reports the derelict ready to take aboard the prize crew ... sir,&quot; he said slowly. &quot;I'd like to volunteer for that detail.&quot;&#10; &#10; I might have let him go under ordinary circumstances, for he was a first class spaceman and the handling of a jury-rigged hulk would need good men. But the gold-hunger I had seen in his eyes warned me to beware. I shook my head. &quot;You will stay on board the Maid with me, Spinelli. Cohn and Zaleski will handle the">
