    <edge source=". Maybe, thinking about the kind of spacemen my generation produced, you have the idea that if ever we'd so much as laid a hand on anything of value out in space we'd not let go until Hell froze over! Well, you're right about that. We didn't seek the spaceways for the advancement of civilization or any of that Foundation bushwah, you can be certain of that. We did it for us ... for Number One. That's the kind of men we were, and we were proud of it. We hung onto what we found because the risks were high and we were entitled to keep what we could out there. But there are strange things in the sky. Things that don't respond to all of our neat little Laws and Theories. There are things that are no part of the world of men, thick with danger—and horror.&#10; &#10; &#10;&#10; &#10; If you doubt that—and I can see you do—just look at me. I suppose you've never heard of the Martian Maid, and so you don't know the story of what happened to her crew or her skipper. I can give you this much of an answer. I was her skipper. And her crew? They ride high in the sky" target="The Martian Maid was a chemical-fueled spaceship, two hundred feet long and armed, that opened up the spaceways. Its crew, including Spinelli, Shelley, Cohn, Marvin, and Zaleski, were a rough bunch of men with a great lust for high pay and hard living. They were not noble pioneers but malcontents and adventuring mercenaries. The narrator, who was the skipper of the Martian Maid, was an ordinary man who didn't know that he was starting out on his last flight when he stood in the valve of the Maid, watching the loading cranes pull away.&#10;&#10;One day, the crew found a derelict ship on a near collision course with the Martian Maid. The narrator fixed the radar on the derelict and computed its orbit, which was strange. He then assembled the ship's company and showed them his figures, indicating that the derelict ship was either abandoned or in distress. However, the crew's unreasoning, unthinking love for gold and their greed led them to take over the derelict ship, which turned out to be a trap. The crew was reduced to jelly at fifty thousand yards by the six-inch supersonic projector abaft the astrogation turret of the derelict ship. The narrator, who had set the radar finder on the Maid's prow squarely on the derelict and kept it aimed dead at it, was the only survivor. He watched as the Maid followed under a steady one G of acceleration with most of her controls on automatic, carrying his greedy crew to their doom. The narrator was left alone, riding high in the sky on a golden ship that his crew had paid for with all the years of their lives.">
