    <edge source="The Martian Maid was a chemical-fueled spaceship, two hundred feet long and armed, that opened up the spaceways. Its crew, including Spinelli, Shelley, Cohn, Marvin, and Zaleski, were a rough bunch of men with a great lust for high pay and hard living. They were not noble pioneers but malcontents and adventuring mercenaries. The narrator, who was the skipper of the Martian Maid, was an ordinary man who didn't know that he was starting out on his last flight when he stood in the valve of the Maid, watching the loading cranes pull away.&#10;&#10;One day, the crew found a derelict ship on a near collision course with the Martian Maid. The narrator fixed the radar on the derelict and computed its orbit, which was strange. He then assembled the ship's company and showed them his figures, indicating that the derelict ship was either abandoned or in distress. However, the crew's unreasoning, unthinking love for gold and their greed led them to take over the derelict ship, which turned out to be a trap. The crew was reduced to jelly at fifty thousand yards by the six-inch supersonic projector abaft the astrogation turret of the derelict ship. The narrator, who had set the radar finder on the Maid's prow squarely on the derelict and kept it aimed dead at it, was the only survivor. He watched as the Maid followed under a steady one G of acceleration with most of her controls on automatic, carrying his greedy crew to their doom. The narrator was left alone, riding high in the sky on a golden ship that his crew had paid for with all the years of their lives." target=" &#10; I was in agony. I didn't want to let anyone get out of my sight with that starship, and at the same time I couldn't leave the Maid. Finally I had to let Cohn take command of the prize crew, but not before I had set the radar finder on the Maid's prow squarely on the derelict.&#10; &#10; &#10;&#10; &#10; Together, Spinelli and I watched the Maid's crew vanish into the maw of the alien ship a